        <pb n="5729" facs="#L1916_2199_img_5729"/>
            <text type="letter" decls="#corresp1">
                <body>
                    

<opener><dateline><date>28/5/16</date></dateline>

<salute>My dearest Mother,</salute></opener>

<p>I have not been treating 
<lb/>you well recently in the 
<lb/>way of letters but really
<lb/> it has been impossible
<lb/> to find time for writing. 
<lb/> Every day it is in the same
<lb/> from early morning till 
<lb/>late at night, one continual
<lb/> rush. </p>  <p>I was so 
<lb/>sorry dear Mother that
<lb/> you have had so much
<lb/> worry with cooks <unclear>etc</unclear>
<lb/> I do wish you could
<lb/> find someone who would
<lb/> suit.</p>  <p>Was glad to get
<lb/> a letter also from Father 
<lb/>with news of the pistol. 
<lb/> If I have time I will
        
    

    
         
        <pb n="5730" facs="#L1916_2199_img_5730"/>
        
        
           
            <lb/>write him a line separately.</p>
<p> We are probably moving
<lb/> back from the Line to&#x2014;
<lb/>morrow or day after.  
<lb/>You see we dont get 
<lb/>much notice, for even
<lb/> yet it is not definite.
<lb/>  We only go a short 
<lb/>distance &amp;, as I understand,
<lb/> for a short time, in order
<lb/> to go through some 
<lb/>special training of a
<lb/> rather strenuous nature, 
<lb/>so it wont mean much
<lb/>rest.  However it will
<lb/> <add>be</add> a little relief from
<lb/> the responsibility of
<lb/> holding the Line. </p>
<p>The weather has not
<lb/> been quite so hot last
<lb/> few days &amp; there has
        
    
         
        <pb n="5731" facs="#L1916_2199_img_5731"/>
        
        
           
            <lb/>been some rain which
<lb/> was really badly needed
<lb/> to lay the dust!  The
<lb/> Germans too have been
<lb/> less vicious so things
<lb/> have been more or less
<lb/> peaceful &amp; it has given
<lb/> us a good opportunity
<lb/> to push on with a lot of
<lb/>rather difficult work. </p>
<p> I spent a most interesting
<lb/> day this week at the 
<lb/>French Machine Gun School
<lb/> some miles from here.
<lb/>  Went with 2 other officers 
<lb/>in a Div. motor &amp; got 
<lb/>back same day.  Saw 
<lb/>no end of interesting
<lb/> things &amp; the French 
<lb/>officers took no end
<lb/> of trouble to show &amp;
        
    
         
        <pb n="5732" facs="#L1916_2199_img_5732"/>
        
        
           
            <lb/>explain everything. </p>
<p> Have sent off a parcel
<lb/> of warm underclothing
<lb/> today &amp; hope it will
l<lb/> turn up all right.  
<lb/>Will have some more
<lb/> to send later. </p> <p> By the
<lb/> way the lining you 
<lb/>sent for my waterproof 
<lb/>was not the right one.
<lb/>  It belonged to one of 
<lb/>my coats at home. 
<lb/> The correct one is very
<lb/> similar &amp; you could
<lb/> easily make a mistake
<lb/> with them.  You can 
<lb/>recognise the one I
<lb/> want as there are
<lb/> elastic bands at
<lb/> wrists &amp; it is rather
<lb/> shorter than the one<pb/>
        
    
         
        <pb n="5733" facs="#L1916_2199_img_5733"/>
        
        
           
            <lb/>you sent.  Would you
<lb/> please have the other
<lb/> sent off &amp; then when
<lb/> it arrives I will send
<lb/> back the one I have.
<lb/>  The parcels from Fureys 
<lb/>&amp; Malcolmsons don't
<lb/> arrive so regularly as
<lb/> they used too but I am
<lb/> sure it is entirely the
<lb/> fault of the P.O. </p>
<p>  Now dearest Mother
<lb/>goodbye.  Don't be
<lb/> alarmed if you do not
<lb/> hear from me for some
<lb/> days as if we <hi rend="underline">do</hi> move
<lb/> it will mean a busy
<lb/> time for me. </p>  <salute>Hoping
<lb/>you are all well &amp; with
<lb/>fondest love
<lb/>Your loving son</salute><signed> Jim</signed>
        
    
         
        <pb n="5734" facs="#L1916_2199_img_5734"/>
        
        
           
            On Active Service
<lb/>written 28<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> May  &#x2014; <gap/>  2nd June
<lb/>19/16

<address>Mrs. S. C. Davidson
<lb/>Seacourt
<lb/>Bangor
<lb/>Co. Down</address>

<lb/>JsDavidson
<date>28 May 1916</date>
        
    
                </body>
            </text>

        
            
        
            
        
            
        
            
        
            
        
            
        

         

